%T A394685 63544,127088,207872,411776,815120,1630240,2314112,4618992,9182760,
%U A394685 17224024,29024656,58049312,91231552,182463104
%N A394685 Number of order-convex subsets of the divisibility poset on {1, 2, ..., n}.
%C A394685 The divisibility poset on {1, ..., n} is ordered by divisibility: a <= b iff a divides b. A subset S is order-convex if whenever a, b in S with a|c|b (a divides c and c divides b), then c in S.
%C A394685 a(n) = 2 * a(n-1) if and only if n is prime. Every prime exactly doubles the count; every composite gives a ratio strictly less than 2. This provides a combinatorial characterization of the primes via convex subsets of the divisibility lattice.
%C A394685 Proof: A prime p <= n has no proper divisors in {2, ..., n} other than multiples of p exceeding p. Including or excluding p from any convex subset is independent of all other elements, so the count exactly doubles. For composite n with a proper divisor d where 1 < d < n, including both n and 1 in a convex subset forces d to be included (since 1|d|n), constraining the count below 2 * a(n-1).
%C A394685 The deficit 2 - a(n)/a(n-1) at composite n correlates with Omega(n) (number of prime factors with multiplicity) at r = 0.857.
%C A394685 The growth rate satisfies log(a(n))/n -> c where c is approximately 0.63.
%H A394685 Thomas DiFiore, <a href="https://github.com/tomdif/causal-algebraic-geometry-lean">Lean 4 formal verification</a>.
%H A394685 Thomas DiFiore, <a href="https://zenodo.org/records/19271288">Causal-Algebraic Geometry</a>, Zenodo.
%F A394685 a(n) = 2 * a(n-1) if and only if n is prime.
%F A394685 a(n) < 2 * a(n-1) if and only if n is composite, n >= 4.
%F A394685 a(n) = 2^pi(n) * C(n) where pi(n) is the prime-counting function and C(n) changes only at composite values of n.
%e A394685 a(1) = 2: the empty set and {1}.
%e A394685 a(2) = 4 = 2*a(1): 2 is prime, so the count doubles. The subsets are {}, {1}, {2}, {1,2}.
%e A394685 a(3) = 8 = 2*a(2): 3 is prime, so the count doubles.
%e A394685 a(4) = 14 < 2*a(3) = 16: 4 is composite (4 = 2^2). Including {1,4} forces inclusion of 2 (since 1|2|4), reducing freedom.
%e A394685 a(5) = 28 = 2*a(4): 5 is prime, so the count doubles.
%o A394685 (Python)
%o A394685 from itertools import combinations
%o A394685 def a(n):
%o A394685     elements = list(range(1, n+1))
%o A394685     count = 0
%o A394685     for r in range(n+1):
%o A394685         for S in combinations(elements, r):
%o A394685             S_set = set(S)
%o A394685             convex = True
%o A394685             for x in S_set:
%o A394685                 for y in S_set:
%o A394685                     if x < y and y % x == 0:
%o A394685                         for z in elements:
%o A394685                             if z not in S_set and z % x == 0 and y % z == 0:
%o A394685                                 convex = False
%o A394685                                 break
%o A394685                     if not convex: break
%o A394685                 if not convex: break
%o A394685             if convex: count += 1
%o A394685     return count
%o A394685 print([a(n) for n in range(1, 11)])  # [2, 4, 8, 14, 28, 48, 96, 156, 296, 550]
%Y A394685 Cf. A393665 (order-convex subsets of [n]^2, square grid), A394682 (order-convex subsets of [n]^3, cubic grid).
%Y A394685 Cf. A000720.
